Sheet1.title: UNFOLD THE ALGORITHM
Sheet1.description:
The algorithm is strange, it adapts to your choice, it’s true that it gives you limited choices, but it is not predetermined like a social code, or social control.
This project mainly looks at the ways writing and reading are reproduced in the context of digital ideology.  This is an attempt to bring to the foreground the hybridity through which knowledge is conceived nowadays; what we want to say, and what we are compelled to say, and how these commercial platforms (Google, Apple products, Yahoo, etc.) function in a ghostly way, like an ideology, leading us to make certain choices without thinking of the conditions that produce them.
We let the iPhone message lead our text, beginning with the word “Algorithm,” then the smartphone gave us three choices to continue (“is,” “is a different,” “for”), we chose “is,” then it gave us three other choices (“a,” “the,” “not”), we chose “a,” and so on… until a sentence was composed by us and the smartphone. We took each word in this sentence and we placed it in the YouTube search engine, and we posted the video YouTube gave us as a first choice for this word. It is interesting to see what were the first choices YouTube gave us, is it first one because it is the most watched, or is it the most watched because it is the first there?

Perhaps the unknown and unexpected is in the result. However, at the same time the result is only an accounted for probability of the algorithm. We (humans) remain to do the unknown and unexpected. In the algorithm we are only a probability, on Google Maps, even when we lose our way, the algorithm seems to always find it. Perhaps only outside the algorithm do we stand a chance for the unknown and unexpected. Outside the algorithm does not necessarily mean we go back to nature and renounce technology, the deep web and the dark web are spaces which are not controlled or determined by algorithms. While algorithms are automated responses to information, programming is a language which hackers for example can bend and twist. Apparently what google and all the search engines that we use can access is 10% of the internet, the rest is divided between the deep web and the dark web. That is where the algorithms don’t function, and all this mediated internet doesn’t exist.
http://unfold.thevolumeproject.com/

Sheet1.title: Ani Liu Algorithmic Animal Gaze
Sheet1.description:
Algorithmic Animal Gaze

Brains, it has recently been argued, are essentially prediction machines. They are bundles of cells that support perception and action by constantly attempting to match incoming sensory inputs with expectations or predictions.(1)

These images are of my body, sorted by how predictable each parcel is to an algorithm that analyzes for compression. Least predictable is sorted from the top left outwards. 

Fascinatingly, the features the computational eye found interesting ended up being the same features human eyes like to dwell on- eyes, lips, breasts, vulva, fingers, nose. 

This set of drawings explore the computational and cognitive eye, as it relates to bodies, vision, cognition, perception.  They were made with computational assistance from Doug von Kohorn.

Sheet1.title: Collecting data
Sheet1.description:
Manovich, Lev, "Database as Symbolic Form", June 1, 1999
https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1177/135485659900500206

Many new media objects do not tell stories; they don't have a beginning or end; in fact, they don't have any development, thematically, formally or otherwise which would organise their elements into a sequence. Instead, they are collections of individual items, where every item has the same significance as any other. Why do new media favour database form over others? Can we explain its popularity by analysing the specificity of the digital medium and computer programming? What is the relationship between database and another form, which has traditionally dominated human culture - narrative?

Sheet1.title: The Thing, Wolfgang Staehle and Collaborators, 1991-95
Sheet1.description:
The Thing (BBS) circa 1994, featuring artwork by Mariko Mori. Photograph courtesy of Wolfgang Staehle

Founded in New York City in 1991, The Thing originated as a Bulletin Board System (BBS)—an early type of online forum—focusing on contemporary art and cultural theory. As a BBS, and later an email provider and ISP, The Thing fostered a community of practitioners who engaged in experiments with political organizing, writing, performance, and the sale and distribution of artwork online.

Including features such as messaging, an anonymized chatroom, and the ability to upload and download files, The Thing BBS initially reached a primarily New York-based community, within reach of local calling rates, but soon grew to include additional nodes in Europe. The project can be considered a platform for contributions by artists and non-artists alike as well as a kind of collectively created social sculpture.
